explanation: "The navicular bone is a boat-shaped tarsal bone located medially in the midfoot between the talus proximally and three cuneiforms distally, serving as the keystone of the medial longitudinal arch.<br><br><img src=\"https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/question_explanation/b081be92-9c59-4595-882f-5dba1491fefd.png\" alt=\"Uploaded Image\"> <br><br>| **Option** | **Verdict** | **Why** |\n| ------ | ------- | --- |\n| **A. Talus** | \u274c | Superior bone, forms ankle joint |\n| **B. Navicular** | \u2705 | **Medial midfoot, anterior to talus** |\n| **C. Lateral calcaneus** | \u274c | Calcaneus is posterior (heel), not midfoot |\n| **D. Medial calcaneus** | \u274c | Calcaneus doesn\u2019t have medial/lateral distinction like this in X-ray ID questions |<br><br>",
